detaileDescriptionText:
Amazon EKS clusters store sensitive information including certificate authorities and service account tokens. When encryption is disabled, this sensitive data is stored in plaintext, potentially exposing it to unauthorized access. Enabling encryption using KMS keys for EKS clusters adds an essential layer of security by encrypting Kubernetes secrets stored in etcd.

To secure your EKS cluster, include the encryption_config block in your Terraform configuration as shown in the following example:
```
resource "aws_eks_cluster" "example" {
  # ... other configuration ...
  encryption_config {
    resources = ["secrets"]
    provider {
      key_arn = "your-kms-key-arn"
    }
  }
}
```
